<p>Containers are a fundamental building block that contain, pad, and align your content within a given device or viewport. The container class can be used in any context.</p>

<p>For each breakpoint the container's width is calculated by <code>calc(100% - 2 * var(--space-m))</code>. This results in a space between container and screen edge. It amounts to <code>1rem</code> without changes to the medium space CSS variable.</p>

<p>This framework comes with three different containers:</p>
<ul>
  <li><code>.container</code>, which sets a <code>max-width</code> at each responsive breakpoint</li>
  <li><code>.container-{breakpoint}</code>, which is fluid until the specified breakpoint</li>
  <li><code>.container-fluid</code>, which is has no <code>max-width</code> at any breakpoints</li>
</ul>

<h2>Default container</h2>

<p>The default <code>.container</code> class is a responsive, fixed-width container, meaning its <code>max-width</code> changes at each breakpoint. Throughout each breakpoint range the container has a <code>max-width</code> equal to the width of the breakpoint width below the active one.</p>

